  "prompt": "Who are the greatest pianists of our age?",
  "response": "Defining \"greatest\" is always subjective, and different people will have different criteria and preferences. Also, defining \"our age\" is somewhat ambiguous, but let's take it to mean roughly the last 30-40 years (post-1980s). With that in mind, here are some pianists who are widely considered among the greatest, grouped by their strengths and areas of focus. This is not an exhaustive list, but it represents a good cross-section of outstanding contemporary pianists:\n\n**Virtuoso Legends & Established Masters:**\n\n*   **Martha Argerich:** (Born 1941)  Known for her fiery temperament, unparalleled technique, and intensely passionate performances. A living legend whose recordings and live performances are always highly anticipated.\n*   **Evgeny Kissin:** (Born 1971) A child prodigy who matured into one of the most technically gifted and emotionally compelling pianists of our time. Renowned for his interpretations of Romantic repertoire.\n*   **Grigory Sokolov:** (Born 1950)  A highly idiosyncratic and deeply intellectual pianist who gives very few concerts and rarely records. Revered for his unique sound and profound interpretations.\n*   **Maurizio Pollini:** (Born 1942)  An intellectual and technically impeccable pianist known for his interpretations of Beethoven, Chopin, and the Second Viennese School.\n*   **Murray Perahia:** (Born 1947)  A deeply thoughtful and lyrical pianist, renowned for his interpretations of Bach, Mozart, and Schubert.  His playing has a profound sense of elegance and refinement.\n*   **Alfred Brendel:** (Born 1931, technically older than the suggested range, but a huge influence).  While his career has largely concluded, Brendel's influence on piano playing is immense.  His analytical and intellectual approach, particularly to Beethoven, Mozart, and Schubert, set a new standard.\n*   **Andr\u00e1s Schiff:** (Born 1953) Another pianist known for his thoughtful interpretations of Bach and Mozart.  He often directs performances from the keyboard.\n\n**Rising Stars and Contemporary Masters:**\n\n*   **Lang Lang:** (Born 1982)  A charismatic and technically dazzling pianist who has brought classical music to a wider audience.  Known for his flamboyant style and passionate performances.\n*   **Yuja Wang:** (Born 1987)  A supremely talented and technically fearless pianist known for her virtuosic playing and captivating stage presence.  Her repertoire is vast and varied.\n*   **Daniil Trifonov:** (Born 1991)  One of the most exciting young pianists on the scene today.  He combines dazzling technique with profound musicality and a distinctive personal voice.\n*   **Igor Levit:** (Born 1987)  A highly intellectual and deeply engaged pianist who uses his platform to address social and political issues. His interpretations are often unconventional and thought-provoking.\n*   **H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Grimaud:** (Born 1969) A pianist and wolf conservationist known for her distinctive interpretations and strong musical personality.\n*   **Leif Ove Andsnes:** (Born 1970)  A Norwegian pianist known for his elegant and insightful interpretations of a wide range of repertoire, from Mozart to contemporary composers.\n*   **Arcadi Volodos:** (Born 1972)  Known for his incredible technical command and the beauty of his tone.\n*   **Pierre-Laurent Aimard:** (Born 1957) A leading interpreter of contemporary music, particularly the works of Ligeti and Messiaen.\n*   **Stephen Hough:** (Born 1961)  A technically brilliant and intellectually stimulating pianist known for his wide-ranging repertoire and insightful interpretations. He's also a writer and composer.\n*   **Mitsuko Uchida:** (Born 1948) Specializes in Mozart, Schubert, and Beethoven.  Known for her clarity, precision, and insightful interpretations.\n\n**Specialists and Niche Masters:**\n\n*   **Marc-Andr\u00e9 Hamelin:** (Born 1961)  A pianist with an encyclopedic knowledge of repertoire, including many rarely performed works. Known for his phenomenal technique and intellectual curiosity.\n*   **Jeremy Denk:** (Born 1969)  A pianist and writer known for his insightful and often humorous essays on music. His performances are both technically impressive and intellectually engaging. He's also a MacArthur Fellow.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Subjectivity:**  Personal taste plays a huge role.  Some people might prefer a pianist with a flamboyant style, while others might prefer a more introspective approach.\n*   **Recordings vs. Live Performance:** A pianist's performance can vary greatly between recordings and live concerts.\n*   **Evolution:** A pianist's artistry evolves over time.\n*   **Specialization:** Some pianists focus on specific composers or styles, becoming leading experts in those areas.\n\nThis list offers a starting point for exploring the world of contemporary pianists. I encourage you to listen to recordings and watch performances of these artists to form your own opinions about who you consider to be the \"greatest.\"\n",
